From: r8q bring-up <r8q@localhost>
Subject: [PATCH] r8q: drm/simpledrm: advertise a DSI connector

On r8q the display is a firmware-lit internal DSI panel that simpledrm scans
out. simpledrm hardcodes DRM_MODE_CONNECTOR_Unknown, so mutter's "is this a
builtin panel" test -- which is purely connector-type based (eDP/LVDS/DSI/DPI)
-- reports the output as an external monitor. mutter only maps an integrated
touchscreen (and applies the output rotation transform to touch coordinates) to
a builtin panel, so with Unknown the touchscreen did not follow display
rotation (portrait was fine, landscape put taps in the wrong place).

Advertise DRM_MODE_CONNECTOR_DSI instead. Combined with a physical size from the
DT (framebuffer `panel` phandle -> width-mm/height-mm), mutter then reports the
output as a "Built-in display" and maps the touch to it. Verified: touch follows
rotation into landscape.
---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/sysfb/simpledrm.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/sysfb/simpledrm.c
@@ -795,8 +795,16 @@
 	/* Connector */

 	connector = &sdev->connector;
+	/*
+	 * r8q: advertise DSI rather than Unknown. On this device simpledrm scans
+	 * out a firmware-lit internal DSI panel; mutter's "is builtin panel"
+	 * test is purely connector-type based (eDP/LVDS/DSI/DPI), and only a
+	 * builtin panel gets an integrated touchscreen mapped to it (and thus
+	 * the output rotation transform applied to touch). Unknown left touch
+	 * un-rotated in landscape.
+	 */
 	ret = drm_connector_init(dev, connector, &simpledrm_connector_funcs,
-				 DRM_MODE_CONNECTOR_Unknown);
+				 DRM_MODE_CONNECTOR_DSI);
 	if (ret)
 		return ERR_PTR(ret);
 	drm_connector_helper_add(connector, &simpledrm_connector_helper_funcs);
